text.b: CLEAR CREEK TRANSIT VILLAGE PROJECT TRAFFIC IMPACT STUDY

page.text: This traffic impact study has been prepared by the Fox Higgins Transportation Group, LLC for
the proposed Clear Creek Transit Village project located on the west side of Federal Blvd. (US
287) roughly 1/3-mile north of the I-76 interchange in Adams County. The purpose of this study
is to identify any potential traffic impacts and to recommend traffic mitigation measures that may
be needed with development of the site as proposed. This study addresses short-term (Year
2015) and long-term (Year 2030) traffic conditions with and without the proposed site
development. Weekday AM and PM peak hour periods were considered for site specific
The project site is located along the west side of US 287 roughly 1/3-mile north of I-76 and 1/3-
Avenue. The site vicinity map is shown on Figure 1. The mixed-use,
transit-oriented project is proposing to develop residential, office, and retail land uses on a 21-
acre parcel of land that is currently unused. The site has previously served a prefab home sales
Access to the site is proposed is proposed, as follows:
• Full-movement, signalized access along Federal Blvd. located along the north site
property line to be shared with the properties to the north and aligned with reconfigured
access on the east side of Federal Blvd.
• Right-in, right-out access along Federal Blvd. roughly 450’ south of the north property
• An emergency-only access along the south site boundary
The preliminary site concept plan is shown on Figure 2. The project vicinity includes existing
commercial development to the north, east, and south. Lake Sangraco borders the site to the
west. An exhibit detailing access modifications at the north access location necessary to
provide shared access for parcels on both the west and east sides of Federal Blvd. is provided

page.text: Descriptions of the existing roadways that serve the site are presented below.
Federal Blvd. (US 287) is a six-lane major arterial categorized as an NR-A facility (Non-Regional
Arterial) by the Colorado Department of Transportation (CDOT). US 287 provides north-south
access through the study area and region. The posted speed limit on Federal Blvd. in the site
Interstate 76 is a four-lane freeway that provides east-west regional access through the study
area, providing access to I-25 to the east and I-70 westbound to the west. The posted speed
limit is 55 mph in the study area. The Federal Blvd. / I-76 interchange is a diamond
configuration with traffic signals located at both the eastbound and westbound ramp terminals.
Avenue is a three-lane minor arterial roadway that provides east-west access for
residential and commercial land uses between Pecos Street to the east and Carr Street to the
Avenue with Federal Blvd. is controlled with a traffic signal.
Existing AM and PM peak hour intersection volumes were collected for this project in August
2009. The existing daily and AM / PM peak hour traffic volumes and lane configurations are
illustrated on Figure 3. The average daily traffic (ADT) volume shown along Federal Blvd.
(34,000 vpd) was obtained from CDOT Year 2009 traffic count data and was factored up to
represent the existing traffic volumes. The existing traffic volumes on Federal Blvd. reflect a
highly directional pattern by time of day, with heavy southbound traffic into Denver in the AM
and heavy northbound traffic from Denver in the PM. Existing traffic volumes at the accesses to
the properties north of the site (both west and east of Federal Blvd) were collected in July 2010
and are summarized on Figure A-1 in the Appendix.
In determining the operational characteristics of an intersection, “Levels of Service” (LOS) A
through F are applied, with LOS A indicating very good operations and LOS F indicating
congested operations. LOS D or better for overall intersection operations and for individual
traffic movements is considered acceptable. Criteria contained in the Highway Capacity
(HCM) was applied to study area intersections using Synchro software in order to
determine existing levels of service during peak hour periods. Additional discussion of LOS
methodology is contained in the Appendix for reference.

text.b: Future Transportation Improvements in the Study Area

page.text: The following information was compiled and reviewed to determine if there are future
transportation system improvements planned within the study area:
• Gold Line Traffic Impacts – Technical Memorandum
• Discussions with CDOT and DRCOG staff.
Based on all of the information reviewed, there are no current plans to widen Federal Blvd. or
provide any other major improvements in the site vicinity in the short or long-term future.
Federal Blvd. is projected to continue to operate as a six-lane roadway north of I-76 and a four
lane roadway south of I-76 through the long-term planning scenario. However, based on the
projected 20-year traffic volumes (discussed in the following section), it is anticipated that
Federal Blvd. will need to be restriped in the vicinity of I-76 to extend the six-lane cross-section
through the north and south I-76 ramp terminal intersections. As discussed in Section 3.7, this
restriping will need to be performed to allow the ramp terminals to service the projected traffic
growth at acceptable levels of service with background traffic growth.

DRCOG Year 2030 traffic model volumes for average weekday conditions were reviewed, along
with historic CDOT traffic growth data, to determine growth rates for the Year 2015 and Year
2030 background scenarios. The existing count of 36,000 vehicles per day (vpd) along Federal
Blvd. was used as a basis for the future-year traffic projections.
Per the DRCOG data, which is included in the appendix, Federal Blvd. is anticipated to service
53,800 vehicles per day (vpd) just north of I-76. This represents a growth rate of approximately
2% annually and includes build out of Gold Line commuter rail sites and other sites along the
Federal corridor. Historic CDOT growth rates predict a 20-year growth factor of 1.20,
corresponding to a 20-year volume of 40,800 vpd, or roughly 0.9% annually. The DRCOG
growth forecasts forecast an average growth rate of approximately 1% annually along W. 64
Since the DRCOG traffic model assumes build out of the Federal Blvd. Gold Line commuter rail
station and adjacent development, site daily traffic volumes were backed out of this 2030 total
volume to represent Year 2030 background traffic volumes. It is estimated that the site will add
roughly 4,800 vpd to Federal Blvd. just north of I-76. Thus, it is anticipated that the traffic
volume along Federal Blvd. adjacent to the site will be approximately 49,000 vpd for the Year
2030 background scenario. Note, this assumes significantly higher growth than the 40,800 vpd
20-year estimate based on the CDOT growth factor but provides a more conservative analysis
Given the DRCOG growth forecasts and CDOT historic growth, an overall 1.5% annual
background traffic growth rate was applied to determine the Year 2015 and Year 2030
background traffic volumes along Federal Blvd. These traffic projections, along with the
anticipated future-year lane geometry, are shown on Figure 4 and Figure 5 for the Year 2015
and Year 2030 background scenarios, respectively. A discussion of the traffic volumes with the
Clear Creek Transit Village trips added is provided in Section 4.2.
In addition to background growth factors, traffic volume specific to the parcels immediately north
of the project site (3.7 acres total) were estimated to assist in planning for the ultimate laneage
for the northern full-movement access. It is assumed that if these parcels redevelop, they will
utilize this shared access for full-movement (signalized) access. In order to estimate these
volumes, it was assumed that the 3.7 acres would be mixed-use with similar uses to the Clear
Creek Transit Village site. However, given the additional distance from the proposed Gold Line
station it was assumed that these sites would have less density (1.25 FAR) and lesser non-auto
use reductions (10%). With approximately 200,000 SF total (50,000 SF retail, 75,000 SF office,
and 75 dwelling units) these sites could potential generate roughly 2,600 primary trips and 300
pass-by trips on a typical weekday. This traffic was distributed onto the Year 2030 network,
including the shared-access along the north border of the site, and is summarized on Figure 5.

It is assumed that Federal Blvd. will be restriped to include three through lanes in each direction
continuous through the south (eastbound) I-76 ramp terminal, as the existing geometry does not
provide enough capacity to support the projected background long-term traffic growth. The
additional capacity is needed to support the heavy southbound AM and northbound PM

the six-lane section only extends south to the north ramp terminal. Physical width exists to
create the six-lane section without widening or impacting the interchange structure, though it
would require restriping single back-to-back left-turn lanes between the ramp terminals. The
interchange currently has side-by-side left-turns, with dual southbound-to-eastbound left-turn

The Clear Creek Transit Village project is proposing to develop roughly 1.5 million square feet of
mixed-use, transit-oriented development taking full advantage of the proposed Federal Blvd.
station along the planned Gold Line commuter rail corridor to be located on the east side of
Federal Blvd. near the site, as well as the Clear Creek Trail and regional trail accessibility. The
project will include high-density residential and office above ground-floor neighborhood retail.
As a transit-oriented development, the project will be designed to promote alternative-mode use
including transit ridership, walking, and bicycling.
Based on the most current development scenario, the project proposes the following land uses
and square feet (SF) per use in six blocks at full build out:
• 1,232 residential dwelling units (both condo and rental units)
Initial, Phase 1 development (within the first five years) is anticipated to include Blocks 1 and 2,
including approximately 400 dwelling units and all of the retail, restaurant, and office uses. The
additional residential units would be developed over the following 5-10 years.

Since the project is proposing a high-density, mixed-use transit-oriented development, it is
anticipated that the site will generate significantly less traffic than the ITE rates predict. The ITE
rates are based primarily on studies that were performed in suburban centers where there is a
lack of transit and alternative mode options. Since the project proposes a mix of uses within a
high-density development, we anticipate that many trips will involve non-auto uses and that
multi-use trips (trips between two or more site land uses) will occur. In order to account for
these trips, reduction factors for non-auto (transit, pedestrian, bicycle) and internal (multi-use
trips) were applied to the ITE rates. Recent studies
developments can generate upwards of 40% less trips than traditional ITE rates. Given that the
area around the Clear Creek Transit Village site may not redevelop as quickly with high-density
uses, we have assumed more modest reductions in this analysis to provide a more conservative
basis for evaluation of site traffic impacts. Based on our experience with similar projects, we
have assumed the following reduction factors for this study:
Reduction: Given the proximity of the planned Gold Line station just east of
the site, a reduction of 15% was assumed for all uses to account for increased transit
and non-auto use compared to the ITE rates.

Due to the nature of the retail and restaurant uses proposed for the project, a percentage of the
automobile traffic entering and exiting the site will be “pass-by” traffic from the adjacent roadway
traffic flows. This traffic currently exists on the adjacent street network and will therefore not be
considered “new” traffic to the overall region. However, these trips will add to the site access
volumes and are accounted for in the site-generated traffic estimates. Thus, pass-by trips are
not a reduction. Given the size of the project and adjacent roadway traffic volumes, it was
assumed that site retail may experience 20% pass-by trips and that the site restaurant would
experience between 43% and 49% pass-by trips, depending upon the specific type of restaurant
(per ITE average rates for each use).

With signalization of the north access roadway intersection with Federal Blvd., full-movement

As proposed, the new signal location at the north access will provide shared access for six
separate properties. Coordination efforts have been ongoing with all of these properties owners
to develop the shared access plan. The addition of a full-movement, signalized access onto
Federal Blvd for these parcels will be an improvement from existing access to and from these
sites. Consolidation of full-movement access at one location will also provide a benefit to
Federal Blvd. by reducing the number of potential conflict points.
Pedestrian and bicycle connections will include sidewalks along Federal Blvd. along the project
frontage and along all internal roadways. Curb extensions to shadow on-street parking will be
provided within the site to shorten crossings for pedestrians, provided better visibility, and
encourage walking to, from, and within the site. A connection to the existing regional multi-use
path alongside Clear Creek is also proposed.
The need for provision of auxiliary turn lanes at the site access intersections is guided by the
criteria contained in the State Highway Access Code. Federal Blvd. currently has three through
lanes in each direction with side-by-side left-turn deceleration lanes provided throughout the
project vicinity. No separate right-turn lanes currently exist along this section of Federal Blvd.
Per the Access Code and based on the 2030 total traffic volumes, a 435’ left-turn deceleration
lane (inclusive of a 13.5:1 taper) plus 345’ of storage for the northbound left-turn lane into the
site should be needed to meet the full Access Code requirement. However, the full Access
Code deceleration and storage lengths are often reduced in urban areas and on the approach to
a signalized intersection, at CDOT’s discretion and given site-specific conditions. NCHRP
criteria for the 45 mph posted speed and Year 2030 volumes would suggest the need for a
northbound left-turn lane to include a minimum of 320’ full lane width for deceleration and
Based on the projected Year 2030 total volumes with redevelopment of the properties north of
the site, dual-left turns will be needed on northbound Federal Blvd. and the width for these lanes
has been provided with the proposed site improvements. With a dual-left turn lane in operation,
the storage requirements will be reduced by 50%.
Per the project site plan, 275’ of storage in one lane (550’) in two lanes can be provided while
still accommodating a 13.5:1 taper and potential future southbound back-to-back left-turn lane at
Avenue, which is likely to be signalized with the addition of the Gold Line station and future
redevelopment. This distance is sufficient to meet the storage requirements for the interim
project condition (with partial build out of the site) as well as the long-term storage requirement
with full build out and redevelopment of the properties to the north. However, while this is
sufficient storage to meet the storage component this distance does not meet the minimum
requirement to include a deceleration/braking component per the CDOT Access Code. Thus, a
variance to the code is necessary for this lane. Given the site location constraints relative to the
existing bridge structure, future signal at 60
Ave, that most arrivals at the left-turn signal will be
on red, and given the urban nature of this site and a comparison to numerous similar accesses
along Federal Blvd. (which do not meet the full code but do not pose safety concerns) we feel
that this variance create any undue potential safety or operational issue.

be landscaped. The raised median also enables the northbound left-turn lane to be pushed
west on the approach to the new signalized north access which provides better visibility
conditions for opposing north-south left-turn traffic at the new signal.

Each MUTCD warrant was considered for this study. However, most of the warrants are not
applicable for this study or it could quickly be determined that they would not be met. Based on
MUTCD criteria, Warrants 1, 2, and 3 are applicable (or very likely will be met) for this study in
the short-term planning horizon. Thus, further analysis of the of the other MUTCD warrants was
The MUTCD states that an intersection with a high-volume of left-turn traffic from the major
street, the signal warrant analysis may be performed in a manner that considered the higher of
the major-street left-turn volumes as the "minor-street" volume and the corresponding single
direction of opposing traffic on the major street as the "major-street" volume. This option is
applicable at the north site access given the project volume of left-turns into the site vs.
opposing through traffic on Federal Blvd. Both the standard MUTCD analysis (based on side
street traffic) and optional main-street left-turn analysis were performed for this project.
Detailed analysis of Warrant 1 (Eight-Hour) and Warrant 2 (Four-Hour) cannot be performed
based on trip generation analysis, since ITE only provides rates for AM and PM peak hours
(only two hours during the day for most land uses). However, based on an extrapolation of the
ITE peak hour and daily trip data it is anticipated that both the four-hour warrant and eight-hour
would be met with short-term development. To meet the four-hour warrant, the site would need
to generate 80 outbound vehicles at the north site access for each any four hours of the day.
This determination is based on the site traffic projections, speed on Federal Blvd (>40 mph
which reduces the volume requirements), and relatively high traffic volumes on Federal Blvd.
Although this site does not meet the “unusual cases” description for the application of Warrant 3
(Peak Hour), this warrant is most often utilized for planning purposes since future trip generation
cannot be accurately estimated on an four or eight-hour basis for Warrants 1 and 2. ITE
typically publishes only peak hour trip rates. Thus, this Warrant was applied for planning
purposes only. A summary of Warrant 3, Peak Hour analysis is shown for the north access
CDOT typically requires that warrant volumes be met prior to the installation of a traffic signal.
At a minimum, initial development of the site should include signal pole bases, conduits, and
other necessary signal infrastructure to allow for future installation of a signal at this location,
pending CDOT approval of this signal location.

of Service” (LOS) A through F are used, with LOS A indicating very good operation and LOS F

could cause substantial delays. Most drivers are restricted in ability to
maneuver and selection of travel speeds due to congestion. Driver comfort
and convenience are low, but tolerable.

travel speeds of one-half to one-third the free flow speed. Vehicular flow is
unstable and there is potential for stoppages of brief duration. High signal
